South Africa is reeling as the looting and unrest continue across Gauteng and KwaZulu-Natal. People are dying, police are being shot at, shopping malls looted and others set on fire. Former National Director of Public Prosecutions, Vusi Pikoli is urging President Cyril Ramaphosa to declare a state of emergency, before it's too late. eNCA anchor, Anlie Hattingh speaks to him for more. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - More calls for government to declare a state of emergency The Beer Industry has added its voice to that of Agri SA and the Consumer Goods Council of SA. READ: Violence in SA: Is a third force at play? Earlier, the Durban Chamber of Commerce and Industry also called for a state of emergency in KwaZulu-Natal. Violent protests and looting have rocked the province following the imprisonment of former president Jacob  Zuma. READ: Violence in SA: Death toll climbs to 72, over 1,200 arrested Seventy-two people have now died in the unrest and over 1,200 have been arrested. Some reports indicate that over 600 retail and liquor stores have been damaged resulting in huge losses.